DURBAN - “It’s in the genes,” said 102-year-old Florence Oldham as her friends cheered on her birthday.
She explained that her grandmother had lived until the ripe old age of 97.
As the candles burnt on her birthday cake at her home in Wentworth yesterday, Oldham spoke of how she remembered Neil Armstrong landing on the moon.
“I remember when the Americans went around in a satellite and a chap whose name was Neil, Neil Armstrong, he was the first man on the moon.”
She also remembered World War II.

“I got married after that.”
Now a great-grandmother twice and a mother of three, Oldham was born in Lusikisiki.
“It was called Pondoland. My mother was a Pondo woman and she married a white man, my father. The whole family of Stoffels, my family, were in Lusikisiki.”AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads

 







